In Week 23 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been building for months came into sharp relief. War abroad, raids at home, and a string of Supreme Court decisions all pointed in the same direction: power moving out of the reach of ordinary checks and into the hands of a smaller circle of actors. The week\'92s events did not abolish elections or close courts. Instead, they showed how a democracy can keep its formal shell while its inner workings are bent toward unilateral rule, selective enforcement, and curated memory. It was a week in which bombs fell on Iran without a vote in Congress, masked agents swept through American cities, and the nation\'92s highest court narrowed the tools available to those who would resist. The pattern was hard to miss.\
\
At the start of the period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:46 p.m. By the end of Week 23, it read 7:49 p.m., a movement of 2.2 minutes toward midnight. That shift captures more than a single decision. It reflects the convergence of several lines of change: an executive branch asserting war powers without effective oversight, a legal system increasingly used as a weapon rather than a limit, security forces aligned with regime priorities over public defense, and a judiciary that, at its apex, now reliably narrows remedies for the vulnerable while expanding room for executive discretion. The clock moved because these trends, already present, deepened and linked together. The week did not mark a sudden collapse. It did mark an acute rupture, a moment when the system\'92s capacity to correct itself visibly shrank.\
\
The most consequential development was the president\'92s decision to bomb Iran\'92s nuclear facilities without congressional authorization. Over the course of the week, multiple accounts converged on the same core facts. On June 21, Trump ordered large-scale airstrikes on three key sites\'97Fordow, Natanz, and Isfahan\'97using B\uc0\u8209 2 bombers, bunker\u8209 busting munitions, and Tomahawk missiles. There was no declaration of war, no prior resolution under the War Powers Act, and, as Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth later admitted, congressional leaders were only notified after the planes were safely out. The operation was announced on social media and then framed in a televised address as a \'93spectacular military success\'94 that had \'93completely and totally obliterated\'94 Iran\'92s enrichment capacity. In constitutional terms, this was a clear assertion that the president could initiate major hostilities on his own authority, with Congress reduced to a spectator. The precedent was stark.\
\
The way the strikes were justified and explained revealed how executive power now operates. In March, the U.S. intelligence community had assessed that Iran was not pursuing a nuclear weapon and had not authorized such a program. That assessment remained in place. Yet in the run\uc0\u8209 up to the bombing, Trump and his senior aides publicly dismissed their own intelligence agencies. The president contradicted his director of national intelligence, Tulsi Gabbard, on camera, insisting that she and the community were \'93wrong.\'94 Vice President J.D. Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio echoed the claim that Iran was racing toward a bomb, while privately relying on Israeli intelligence that U.S. analysts did not share. After the strikes, a Defense Intelligence Agency report concluded that Iran\'92s program had been set back only a few months and that much of its enriched uranium had been moved in advance. Rather than prompt a reassessment, that report was denounced by the White House as inaccurate, and its leak became the subject of a criminal investigation. Intelligence that supported the president\'92s narrative was amplified; intelligence that did not was sidelined or treated as a security breach.\
\
Congress\'92s response showed both the persistence of institutional forms and their weakening force. Some members, including Senator Chris Van Hollen and Representative Sean Casten, denounced the bombing as unconstitutional and called for strict adherence to the War Powers Resolution. A group of House Democratic veterans rallied behind a resolution to limit Trump\'92s authority to wage war in Iran, citing the lessons of Iraq and Afghanistan. Representative Thomas Massie, a Republican, joined with Democrat Ro Khanna in a bipartisan effort to reassert legislative control. Yet when articles of impeachment were introduced over the unauthorized strikes, the House voted to table them, with only 79 Democrats willing to proceed. The Republican majority showed no appetite to confront the president, and even many Democrats hesitated to use their strongest tool. In the Senate, the administration canceled or postponed classified briefings without explanation, and then announced plans to restrict congressional access to sensitive intelligence after the DIA leak. The legislature protested, but it did not compel compliance. Its checks remained mostly on paper.\
\
The courts, too, were active, but their ability to shape outcomes narrowed at the top. At the district and circuit levels, judges issued a series of rulings that checked some of the administration\'92s more aggressive moves. A federal judge ordered the release of Mahmoud Khalil, a Palestinian activist and legal resident, after more than 100 days in ICE detention, finding no evidence that he was a danger or a flight risk. Another court ordered the government to seek the return of Jordin Melgar\uc0\u8209 Salmeron, deported to El Salvador less than half an hour after a judge had barred his removal. A New York judge blocked Trump\'92s attempt to use the Alien Enemies Act to deport Venezuelan migrants, rejecting the claim that they constituted an \'93invasion.\'94 In the environmental sphere, a district court enjoined the administration from withholding $5 billion in electric\u8209 vehicle charger funds that Congress had already appropriated. These decisions showed that, case by case, lower courts could still enforce statutory limits and due process. They were real, but they were narrow.\
\
The Supreme Court moved in a different direction. In a cluster of 6\'963 decisions, the conservative majority curtailed the tools available to challenge federal and state power. In one ruling, the Court held that Medicaid beneficiaries lack a private right to sue when states restrict their choice of provider, a decision that clears the way for states to exclude Planned Parenthood from Medicaid without facing suits from patients. In another, it upheld a Texas law requiring age verification for access to pornography websites, despite concerns about privacy and free expression. Most consequential for structural power, the Court sharply limited lower courts\'92 ability to issue nationwide injunctions. In cases consolidated under Trump v. CASA, involving an executive order that sought to deny birthright citizenship to some children of non\uc0\u8209 citizen parents, the Court stayed universal injunctions and held that such broad relief likely exceeded judicial authority. Going forward, injunctions would generally protect only the named plaintiffs, unless class\u8209 action status were granted. This shift does not change the text of the Constitution. It changes how quickly and broadly unconstitutional policies can be halted.\
\
While war and doctrine occupied the formal branches, the security apparatus at home was being repurposed. Immigration enforcement was the main field of experimentation. ICE raids intensified in Los Angeles and other cities, with agents increasingly operating in masks and plain clothes, often without clear warrants. In Los Angeles, the sweeps were so pervasive that no\uc0\u8209 show rates at community health clinics tripled, as patients feared arrest on the way to appointments. Businesses closed early, parents kept children home, and even U.S. citizens of color began to avoid public spaces. One 32\u8209 year\u8209 old citizen, Andrea Velez, was seized on her way to work; witnesses said agents did not ask for identification and appeared to target her based on appearance. Her family could not locate her for more than a day. In Georgia, a 68\u8209 year\u8209 old man died while being transported by a private contractor from a local jail to a federal detention center, the first such death in at least a decade. In Louisiana, a pregnant detainee, Iris Dayana Monterroso\u8209 Lemus, lost her baby after reporting starvation and denial of medical care. These were not isolated mishaps. They were symptoms of a system under pressure to meet quotas.\
\
Those quotas were explicit. In a May meeting, White House deputy chief of staff Stephen Miller and DHS Secretary Kristi Noem ordered ICE to increase arrests to 3,000 per day. By Week 23, ICE facilities held more than 56,000 people, exceeding capacity and producing overcrowded, unsanitary conditions. To house this surge, the administration moved to expand detention infrastructure. In California, ICE partnered with CoreCivic to convert a shuttered 2,500\uc0\u8209 bed prison into the state\'92s largest immigrant detention center, over local opposition. In Florida, state and federal authorities advanced plans for a 5,000\u8209 bed camp in the Everglades, quickly dubbed \'93Alligator Alcatraz.\'94 Governor Ron DeSantis used emergency powers to seize 39 square miles of land from Miami\u8209 Dade County for the project, bypassing normal environmental and local\u8209 governance processes. Environmental groups and the Miccosukee Tribe sued, arguing that the project could not proceed without a full environmental study. The facility would be built in tents, guarded by National Guard troops, and funded by both Florida taxpayers and DHS. In this way, emergency authority and federal dollars combined to embed a long\u8209 term carceral landscape into the immigration system.\
\
The line between law enforcement and political intimidation grew thinner. In Newark, federal prosecutors charged Mayor Ras Baraka with trespass after he entered an ICE detention center, and Representative LaMonica McIver with assaulting law enforcement during the same incident. Both said they were conducting oversight of detention conditions. The charges against Baraka were dropped after ten days, and a magistrate judge later rebuked prosecutors for their haste, suggesting they had failed to investigate before wielding their power. McIver, however, was indicted on three counts and pleaded not guilty, calling the case political intimidation. In New York, ICE agents arrested city comptroller and mayoral candidate Brad Lander when he asked to see a warrant during an arrest he was observing; the charges were later dropped. These episodes sent a clear message: officials who challenge immigration enforcement on the ground may find themselves in handcuffs.\
\
Inside the Justice Department, the same pattern appeared in more rarefied form. A whistleblower, former DOJ lawyer Erez Reuveni, alleged that Emil Bove, the principal associate deputy attorney general and a Trump judicial nominee, had urged subordinates to ignore court orders blocking deportations under the Alien Enemies Act. According to Reuveni, Bove argued that removal flights could proceed as long as planes left U.S. airspace before a written order was issued, even if a verbal temporary restraining order had already been granted. Reuveni refused to go along and was later terminated. In a separate matter, Bove directed the dismissal of bribery and conspiracy charges against New York City Mayor Eric Adams, over the objections of line prosecutors, in exchange for Adams\'92s cooperation with Trump\'92s immigration agenda. A judge dismissed the case with prejudice and criticized Bove\'92s rationale as incompatible with equal justice. Bove also authored memos that led to the firing of prosecutors and FBI agents who had worked on January 6 cases, describing their efforts as a \'93grave national injustice.\'94 Through these actions, the Justice Department\'92s top ranks were reshaped to favor loyalty and policy alignment over independent enforcement.\
\
The Supreme Court\'92s immigration decisions intersected with these executive moves to create a stratified regime of belonging. By allowing deportations to third countries with little process, and by staying injunctions that had blocked Trump\'92s birthright\uc0\u8209 citizenship order nationwide, the Court made it easier for the administration to redraw the boundaries of who counts as American. At the same time, the administration terminated Temporary Protected Status for more than half a million Haitians, giving them just over two months to leave or find another status, and explored agreements with 53 countries\'97many with poor human\u8209 rights records\'97to hold deported individuals. It also announced plans to resettle 1,000 Afrikaners from South Africa while barring refugees from countries under the travel ban. In Congress, Representative Andy Ogles called for the denaturalization and deportation of Zohran Mamdani, a Muslim democratic socialist who had just won the Democratic mayoral primary in New York City, labeling him \'93antisemitic\'94 and a \'93communist.\'94 He sent a letter to the attorney general citing statutes that allow revocation of citizenship for those who misrepresent support for terrorism. Democrats on the House Homeland Security Committee condemned his remarks as \'93racist drivel,\'94 but the episode showed how denaturalization, once a rare legal tool, was being floated as a partisan weapon.\
