While the coercive side of the state expanded, institutions of knowledge and communication were being bent to political ends. The most visible case was Voice of America. The administration authorized the termination of 639 VOA employees, the final phase of a campaign that had eliminated 1,400 positions since March and reduced the U.S. Agency for Global Media to about 250 staff. Officials had long derided VOA as \'93leftist propaganda\'94 and sought to fold it back into the State Department. A federal judge criticized the administration for failing to comply with an injunction related to earlier mass firings, questioning its commitment to statutory obligations. Yet the cuts went forward, effectively dismantling a major independent public broadcaster at the moment when the government\'92s own narrative about war and immigration was under greatest scrutiny.\
