In public health, a similar capture unfolded. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. had already fired all 17 members of the CDC\'92s Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices and replaced them with eight appointees known for spreading vaccine misinformation. During a House hearing, he defended deep budget cuts and the elimination of entire offices in the public health sector, arguing that they targeted duplicative functions. Representative Kim Schrier accused him of lying to Senator Bill Cassidy about not firing the vaccine advisory committee; Kennedy denied making any such promise. At the reconstituted ACIP meeting, five of the new members voted to restrict the use of thimerosal in flu vaccines, despite decades of evidence showing no harm from the preservative and warnings that such a move could reduce global vaccine availability. A CDC presentation by Lyn Redwood, a former anti\uc0\u8209 vaccine activist now in HHS, cited a study that does not exist, claiming long\u8209 term brain effects from thimerosal. At the same time, the administration proposed a 37 percent cut\'97$2.7 billion\'97to the National Cancer Institute\'92s budget, prompting warnings from experts that research would stall and more patients would die. The Supreme Court, in Kennedy v. Braidwood Management, upheld the constitutionality of the Affordable Care Act\'92s preventive\u8209 services mandate but clarified that the health secretary has broad power to appoint and remove members of the preventive services task force. In combination, these moves left the formal structure of health coverage intact while placing the levers of scientific recommendation in the hands of an ideologically driven secretary.\
