The information environment around elections and legitimacy continued to be flooded with elite\uc0\u8209 driven narratives. Trump renewed his call for a special prosecutor to investigate baseless claims of fraud in the 2020 election, years after courts and audits had rejected them. He and his allies pursued legal and media campaigns alleging that networks like CBS and Fox had engaged in \'93election interference\'94 through editing and commentary. A mediator proposed a $20 million settlement in Trump\'92s lawsuit against CBS over a 60 Minutes interview with Kamala Harris, with most of the money to be donated to a Trump foundation or museum; negotiations stalled over Trump\'92s demand for an apology. California Governor Gavin Newsom sued Fox News and host Jesse Watters for $787 million, claiming they had aired a deceptively edited clip that falsely portrayed him as lying about a call with Trump. Media Matters for America sued the FTC, alleging that Trump appointees had retaliated against it for reporting on extremist content on Twitter. These suits and counter\u8209 suits did not resolve the underlying disputes over truth. They showed how defamation law and regulatory power were being used as weapons in a broader struggle over who gets to define reality.\
