Against this backdrop, there were still signs of democratic resilience. Voters in New York City chose Zohran Mamdani as the Democratic nominee for mayor, making him the first Muslim and South Asian candidate to win that primary. His platform\'97raising taxes on the wealthy, freezing rents on stabilized apartments, building 200,000 units of affordable housing, making buses free, and providing universal childcare\'97challenged the city\'92s economic status quo. His victory inspired thousands of progressives to consider running for office. A Quinnipiac poll showed that 64 percent of registered voters supported a path to legalization for undocumented immigrants, and a majority disapproved of Trump\'92s handling of deportations. Young voters\'92 approval of the president had dropped sharply. In the courts, judges continued to enforce limits where they could, from blocking the EV charger fund freeze to ordering the return of wrongfully deported individuals. Civil society groups organized protests against Medicaid cuts and Palantir\'92s ICE contracts, accepting arrest as the price of visibility. These acts did not reverse the week\'92s structural shifts, but they kept alive alternative centers of power and narrative.\
